Many of Weiner's language works carry idiomatic connotations. For example, the piece " Illuminated by the Lights of Two Ships Passing in the Night " derives from the English phrase "ships passing in the night," which conveys the idea of people who meet briefly and intensely to never see each other again after. However, when this phrase is displayed in the great hall, the saying transforms into a physical form that visitors perceive according to scale and presentation. For native English speakers, encountering this phrase in everyday contexts typically evokes its idiomatic meaning, but Weiner's presentation prompts a shift, leading one to vividly imagine the literal scene of two ships meeting.
The exploration of relationships between things is a central theme of this exhibition in UCCA. Many works in the exhibition address the relationships between distinct entities —things that are set apart, things that connect, and things that connect while remaining distinct. This theme may also resonate with today's geopolitical environment as well as reflect Weiner's belief that "art is the relationship of human beings to objects and objects to objects in relation to human beings."

Lawrence Weiner's practice has always been multilingual. His works exhibited globally, often in English alongside translations into local languages. The issue of translatability is central to his work, which is why we've placed A TRANSLATION FROM ONE LANGUAGE TO ANOTHER prominently in the Great Hall, to highlight the importance of this theme when approaching his works. Weiner treats language as a sculpting material, and many of his language pieces refer to specific materials and circumstances that leave little room for misinterpretation. This approach lends his work a sense of translatability, often necessitating literal translations. However, Weiner's language works often resemble unfinished sentences or actions suspended in time, and he frequently engages with idiomatic phrases and self-referential looping, leaving room for openness and ambiguity in their translation.
Translating Weiner's work is a continual challenge - finding the right balance between preserving the original, literal meaning and capturing the idiomatic nuances that transcend the words themselves. This exhibition at UCCA, this exhibition marks the first time a large body of Weiner's work has been translated into Chinese. While perfect translations are impossible, these efforts invite discussion among the "receivers" of his work, whom Weiner had always held in the highest regard.
